<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="07d43cf4-6168-5ee4-844b-b9d6554d26a0" activityNameId="ac1afcd4-327a-426e-a87f-36ffe1bbea67" parentActivityId="0a153624-08ce-42ca-bf9c-4cbd6aa10290" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">propylene production, from propane dehydrogenation</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">propene</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">PDH</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">From the reception of propane at the factory gate.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with propylene being ready for further processing or transportation at the production site gate. Infrastructure is included.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This process represents the production of 1 kg of propylene from propane dehydrogenation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dehydrogenation of light alkanes (i.e., propane and butane) attracted significant attention for the selective large-scale production of light olefins. During the dehydrogenation reaction, two carbon-hydrogen bonds break leading to the production of hydrogen, as valuable byproduct, and the formation of a carbon-carbon double bond. The economic viability of the selectrive production of olefins via dehydrogenation is influenced by the market price of the feedstock, i.e., alkanes, and the the valuable products, i.e., olefins. Notably, the propane dehydrogenation technology allows the on-purpose production of propylene (as the main reference product) and thus, shifting from its conventional production as a byproduct in steam crackers.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">There are several proceseses, for dehydrogenation, explored commercially. This dataset describes the Oleflex process. The processes mainly distinguish in their catalyst use and regeneration. Propane dehydrogenation processes are highly selective, overall yields of propylene production of up to 90 % are claimed.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In the China, 30% of propylene are produced by refineries, 27% by steam cracking, 19% by propane dehydrogenation and 24% by coal to olefin.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Eisele P.,Killpack R. (2011): Propene, Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemisty, Wiley-VCH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Lv, L.; Song, G.; Zhao, X.; Chen, J. (2021): Environmental Burdens of China’s Propylene manufacturing: Comparative life-cycle assessment and scenario analysis, Science of the Total Environment, 799, 149451.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Nawaz, Z. (2015). Light alkane dehydrogenation to light olefin technologies: a comprehensive review. Reviews in chemical engineering, 31(5), 413-436.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0c40fa1e-7d7e-11de-9ae2-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">CN</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Inventory based on a Chinese production plant.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">There are several proceseses explored commercially, this dataset describes the Oleflex process. The processes are distinguished mainly based on their catalyst use and regeneration. Propane dehydrogenation processes are highly selective, overall yields of propylene from propane up to 90 % are claimed.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The propane feed is admitted to a moving-bed catalytic reactor. In a continuous process, the dehydrogenation catalyst circulates through the reaction vessel before passing to a separate regeneration vessel where coke is removed from the surface of the catalyst by combustion in air. The regenerated catalyst is returned to the first reactor.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Propene is recovered by conventional deethanizer – depropanizer splitting.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">An overall selectivity for propene of 89 – 91% is claimed.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">The chemical reaction of the reaction is:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">C3H8 --&gt; C3H6 + H2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">The reaction is catalysed by a platinum-based catalyst, due to lack of data the catalyst was neglected.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Eisele P.,Killpack R. (2011): Propene, Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemisty, Wiley-VCH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Lv, L.; Song, G.; Zhao, X.; Chen, J. (2021): Environmental Burdens of China’s Propylene manufacturing: Comparative life-cycle assessment and scenario analysis, Science of the Total Environment, 799, 149451.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2022-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Based on a scientific publication. The technology is not expected to change over time.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
